1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,000
Have you ever felt that your admin settings weren't personalized enough to meet your needs?

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,000
Well, in this workshop, we'll have you configure your writing settings to help streamline all new blog posts.

3
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:14,000
I'm going to start from the dashboard of my food blog and hover over settings on the left navigation bar and click on "Writing".

4
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:23,000
You'll see the default post category is our first option on the top.

5
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:27,000
If you already have existing post categories, you'll be able to change the default option here.

6
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:33,000
You'll see Uncategorized usually comes preselected, which means I would manually need to select a different category with each new post.

7
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:42,000
I want mine to automatically go to my Recipes category, since that's what I use most often.

8
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:47,000
And now when I go to my food blog, you'll see under categories that Recipe is already selected as that new default.

9
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:55,000
Let's go to the second option under writing settings, which is default post format.

10
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:00,000
You'll see different options in the dropdown list, depending on the theme you have installed.

11
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:05,000
So for instance, I'm going to change my post format to an image, since I usually start every post in my food blog with a picture.

12
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,000
And now, when I go to make a new post, you'll see that the post is ready for me to add a new image.

13
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:21,000
Next, you'll find a unique feature that allows you to write and publish posts right from your email.

14
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:28,000
To use this feature, you'll need to create an email account with POP3 Access.

15
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:33,000
If you've got an email through your WordPress hosting provider, it'll probably work, or you could use other options like Gmail or Yahoo!

16
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:41,000
Just make sure your email is secret and difficult to guess.

17
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:45,000
WordPress will give a series of random strings that you could use for the email.

18
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:50,000
Any email sent to this account once it's set up will result in a blog post.

19
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:54,000
That's why you want to keep it secret.

20
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:57,000
There's a catch here, though.

21
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:58,000
WordPress has stated that this feature may be removed in an upcoming release.

22
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:03,000
So if any of the above situations sound like they'd be helpful to you, I recommend checking out some posts by email plugins.

23
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:09,000
The last section in writing settings is update services.

24
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:13,000
This refers to blog-rolling services like Pingomatic, which let other people know that you've updated your blog.

25
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:19,000
You can add any other blog-rolling services in this box, and if you've updated or changed these settings, go ahead and click Save Changes.

26
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:28,000
Great job personalizing your writing settings.

